{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e8bcc1ef-640e-4609-807f-bf011ead3a2a","content":"The template is **close but not quite ready**. Here's what I found:\n\n**✅ Good:**\n- Required fields present: `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`\n- `sourceName`, `classifications`, and `tags` are properly set\n- `tags.type` = `\"project\"` and `tags.language` = `\"C#\"` are correct\n\n**⚠️ Issues to fix:**\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for tooling/validation support.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages so templates can be grouped across versions (e.g., `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi.CSharp\"`).\n\n3. **`Framework` symbol has no `replaces`** — The parameter is defined but never substitutes into source files. You need `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (matching the literal in your `.csproj`) for the choice to actually take effect.\n\nWithout #3 especially, the framework selector is non-functional. Want me to apply these fixes?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4611550d-7430-4df5-ae19-f92c4c9061ec","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but highly recommended for tooling/validation. The standard schema URL is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet package templates so multiple templates can be grouped.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of a template exist.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n\n\n5. **`sourceName`**, `identity`, `shortName`, `author`, `classifications`, and `tags`** are all present and properly configured. The main gap is that the Framework parameter lacks a `replaces` property to actually substitute the value into the `.csproj` file, so right now it's defined but won't have any effect on the generated project.\n\n6. Looking at what's actually required versus recommended: the core fields like `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, and `author` are all there, but for NuGet publishing I'd want to add `$schema` and `groupIdentity` for better discoverability. The Framework symbol really needs that `replaces` mapping to work properly—it should point to the `<TargetFramework>` element in the project file.","outputTokens":869,"requestId":"4046:1F3FEB:E8309D6:1014F6B6:69EC0F91"},"id":"02d823dd-c61e-4758-a0ad-6fbde5fa538e","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:49:38.863Z","parentId":"8b8e3dea-6374-4d9c-8d6f-d3dad3d38e77"}
